4. APPLICATION ENTRY POINT (app/main.py)
================================================================================

The file app/main.py is where the FastAPI application is created and all middleware is registered.
It is also responsible for startup and shutdown events.

HOW IT IS BUILT:

  The FastAPI app uses the "lifespan" context manager (a modern alternative to @app.on_event).
  On startup, it performs two critical initialization steps:

  Step 1 — Database Bootstrap:
    Base.metadata.create_all(bind=engine) is called. This tells SQLAlchemy to inspect all ORM
    model classes (Session, ChatLog, TrainingData) and automatically CREATE the corresponding
    MySQL tables if they do not already exist. This means the app is self-initializing — no
    manual SQL is required on first run.

  Step 2 — ML Model Loading:
    The global IntentClassifier instance is loaded from disk using classifier.load(). This reads
    the serialized model file from ml_models/intent_model.joblib.
    - If the file exists: the model is loaded and ready immediately.
    - If the file does NOT exist but ml_data/intent_training.csv exists: the model is automatically
      trained from scratch using the CSV data, then saved to disk.
    - If neither exists: a warning is printed and the API still starts (but will return "unknown"
      for all classifications until the model is trained via POST /api/train).

  CORS Middleware:
    Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) is configured so the web-app (running on a different
    port, e.g., localhost:5173) can make API requests to the backend (localhost:8000). The allowed
    origins are loaded from the CORS_ORIGINS environment variable so they can be changed without
    editing code.

  Rate Limiter:
    The slowapi limiter instance is attached to app.state.limiter. This injects the rate limiter
    into FastAPI's dependency injection system so individual routes can apply per-route limits.
    A custom exception handler converts RateLimitExceeded exceptions into clean HTTP 429 responses.

  Root Route:
    A root GET / endpoint returns basic information (name, version, docs URL, health URL) so
    developers know the API is running without needing to check documentation.


