6. MACHINE LEARNING PIPELINE
================================================================================

The ML pipeline is the brain of the system. It converts raw, free-form user text into a
structured intent classification that the rest of the application can act on.

────────────────────────────────────────────────
6a. TEXT PREPROCESSING (app/ml/preprocessing.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────

Before any text goes into the classifier, it is preprocessed by preprocess_text(). This is
critical for good classification accuracy because raw user text contains noise (punctuation,
capital letters, stopwords) that would confuse TF-IDF.

The preprocessing pipeline, applied in order:

  1. LOWERCASING
     All characters are converted to lowercase. "What is PDID 001" becomes "what is pdid 001".
     This prevents the model from treating "What" and "what" as different tokens.

  2. WHITESPACE NORMALIZATION
     Multiple spaces, tabs, and newlines are collapsed into a single space using regex.

  3. PDID PATTERN NORMALIZATION
     The regex pattern r"pdid[\s\-_]*(\d+)" normalizes all PDID formats to a standard form.
     - "PDID-001" → "pdid 001"
     - "PDID001"  → "pdid 001"
     - "pdid 001" → "pdid 001" (unchanged)
     This ensures the classifier always sees the same representation regardless of how the user
     writes the PDID reference.

  4. PUNCTUATION REMOVAL
     Most punctuation is stripped. Only these characters are kept:
     - Hyphens (-): used in PDID patterns
     - Question marks (?): help distinguish questions from statements
     - Exclamation marks (!): help detect complaints
     Filipino characters (ñ, accented vowels like á, é, í, ó, ú) are also explicitly preserved
     so Filipino-language messages are not corrupted.

  5. STOPWORD REMOVAL
     Common English and Filipino stopwords are removed to reduce noise in TF-IDF features.
     English stopwords include: a, an, the, is, are, have, do, will, I, me, my, we, you, it, etc.
     Filipino stopwords include: ang, ng, sa, na, ay, mga, si, at, o, din, rin, pa, lang, etc.
     Removing stopwords ensures TF-IDF focuses on meaningful content words.

  FINAL RESULT: A clean, normalized string ready for TF-IDF vectorization.
  Example: "What is the current status of my document?" → "current status document ?"

────────────────────────────────────────────────
6b. INTENT CLASSIFIER (app/ml/intent_classifier.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────

The IntentClassifier class wraps a scikit-learn Pipeline that converts text to a classified
intent with a probability score. This is the core ML model.

ALGORITHM: TF-IDF + SGDClassifier (Stochastic Gradient Descent)

  WHY TF-IDF?
  TF-IDF (Term Frequency–Inverse Document Frequency) converts text into a numeric vector. Each
  word becomes a dimension. Words that appear a lot in one class but rarely across all classes
  get higher weights — these are the "distinguishing" words. For example, "status" and "document"
  are strong signals for document_status intent.

  Configuration used:
    - ngram_range=(1, 2): Uses both single words AND consecutive word pairs (bigrams).
      This means "check document" is a feature in addition to "check" and "document" separately.
      Bigrams capture more context and dramatically improve accuracy for short intents.
    - max_features=5000: Only the 5000 most informative features are retained to keep the
      model small and fast.
    - sublinear_tf=True: Applies log scaling to term frequencies (1 + log(tf)) to reduce the
      impact of very frequent terms.

  WHY SGDClassifier?
  SGDClassifier is a linear classifier trained with stochastic gradient descent. It is extremely
  fast and handles multi-class classification well. It was chosen over alternatives like SVM or
  Naive Bayes because:
    - It supports online learning (can be retrained incrementally in theory)
    - With "modified_huber" loss function, it natively supports predict_proba() for confidence scores
    - class_weight="balanced" automatically compensates for imbalanced class sizes in training data

  THE PIPELINE:
    pipeline = Pipeline([
        ("tfidf", TfidfVectorizer(...)),
        ("clf", SGDClassifier(...)),
    ])
  The Pipeline chains the vectorizer and classifier together so predict() automatically
  preprocesses → vectorizes → classifies in one call.

TRAINING:
  The train() method accepts either a CSV filepath or a list of (text, intent) tuples.
  - Each text sample is passed through preprocess_text() first
  - The pipeline is fit on all samples at once
  - Training accuracy is calculated immediately after fitting (on training data)
  - The trained pipeline is saved to ml_models/intent_model.joblib using joblib.dump()
  - Training stats (sample count, intent count, accuracy) are returned for API response

LOADING:
  The load() method reads the serialized .joblib file from disk using joblib.load(). The entire
  scikit-learn pipeline object is deserialized, including both the TF-IDF vocabulary weights
  and the SGD classifier weights. This takes milliseconds.

PREDICTION:
  The predict() method:
  1. Preprocesses the raw input text
  2. Calls pipeline.predict() to get the most likely intent label
  3. Calls pipeline.predict_proba() to get confidence probabilities for ALL intents
  4. Takes the maximum probability as the confidence score
  5. If confidence < CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD (default 0.4), returns ("unknown", confidence)
     instead of a low-confidence prediction — preventing hallucinated responses
  6. Returns (intent_label, confidence_score) as a tuple

INTENT CLASSES (from training data):
  - document_status: User wants to know the status of a document
  - follow_up:       User is providing a PDID in response to being asked
  - greeting:        User says hello, hi, good morning, etc.
  - help:            User asks what the bot can do
  - complaint:       User expresses frustration or complaints
  - thanks:          User says thank you
  - goodbye:         User says bye, see you, etc.
  - unknown:         Anything that doesn't fit with enough confidence

────────────────────────────────────────────────
6c. ENTITY EXTRACTOR (app/ml/entity_extractor.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────

While the classifier identifies WHAT the user wants to do, the entity extractor identifies the
KEY DATA in the message — specifically the PDID (document tracking number).

Regex is used instead of ML for entity extraction because PDIDs are structured and predictable.
Regex is faster, more reliable, and doesn't require training data for this purpose.

THREE PATTERNS ARE TRIED IN ORDER OF SPECIFICITY:

  Pattern 1 (Explicit "PDID" keyword):
    r"(?i)\bpdid[\s\-_]*(\d{1,10})\b"
    Matches: "PDID 001", "PDID-001", "PDID001", "pdid001", "pdid 1000", etc.
    The (?i) flag makes it case-insensitive.

  Pattern 2 (PDID with connector words):
    r"(?i)\bpdid\s+(?:is|number|no\.?|num)\s+(\d{1,10})\b"
    Matches: "My PDID is 007", "PDID number 003", "PDID no. 100"
    This handles more verbose user phrasing.

  Pattern 3 (Standalone number — follow-up context):
    r"^\s*(\d{1,10})\s*$"
    Matches ONLY if the entire message is just a number (e.g., the user types "001").
    This handles the common scenario where the bot asks "What is your PDID?" and the
    user replies with just the number.

NORMALIZATION:
  Once a PDID is extracted, it is normalized:
  - Leading zeros are stripped: "001" → "1"
  - Then zero-padded to 3 digits: "1" → "001"
  This ensures "1", "01", and "001" are all treated as the same document.

RESULT:
  Returns {"pdid": "001"} if a PDID is found, or {} if no entities were extracted.


