8. DTS API CLIENT (app/services/dts_client.py)
================================================================================

The DTS client handles all interaction with the document tracking backend. It supports two modes:
mock mode (for development/testing) and live mode (for production with the real DTS API).

RESPONSE PARSER: parse_dts_document()
  The real DTS API returns a deeply nested JSON structure. This function flattens it into a
  simple, AI-friendly dict. It extracts:

  - Basic metadata: pdid, title, agency, origin_office, subject, created_at, created_by
  - Status determination:
      * "Completed" if document_completed_status is True
      * "In Progress" if the last route stop has no date_out (still being processed)
      * "In Transit" if routes exist but the last stop has a date_out
  - Current location: the last route stop's office name
  - Current holder: the last employee who performed an action on the document
  - Route history: a list of every office the document has passed through, including
    received_at and date_out timestamps, the responsible person, and their action
  - The numbered prefix in office names (e.g., "1. City Health Office") is stripped to "City Health Office"
  - Photo URL: if an employee profile photo path is available, the full URL is built by
    prepending the DTS_API_BASE_URL

  The parser handles two response formats:
  - Wrapped: { "success": true, "data": { ... } }  — used by mock data / documents.json
  - Root-level: { "id": ..., "title": ..., ... }   — used by the live DTS API

MOCK MODE:
  MOCK_DOCUMENTS is a dictionary populated at startup by _load_mock_data(). It first tries to
  load a real DTS response from documents.json in the project root. If that file exists and is
  valid JSON, it is parsed using parse_dts_document() and added to the mock dict. Then, three
  built-in sample documents (PDIDs 001, 002, 003) are added as fallback entries if their keys
  aren't already in the dict. The built-in samples already exist in flat/parsed format.

LIVE MODE:
  When DTS_MOCK_MODE is False, get_document() makes an async HTTP GET request using httpx to:
    GET {DTS_API_BASE_URL}/api/documents/{pdid}
  The response is parsed with parse_dts_document() and then cached in the TTLCache for 60 seconds.
  This means if multiple users look up the same PDID within a minute, only one HTTP call is made.
  404 responses (document not found) are also cached to avoid hammering the DTS API with not-found requests.

CACHING:
  _document_cache is a TTLCache(maxsize=256, ttl=60). It holds up to 256 documents in memory
  for up to 60 seconds each. After 60 seconds, entries expire and the next lookup hits the real API.

PDID NORMALIZATION:
  PDIDs go through normalization before lookup:
  - pdid.strip().lstrip("0") or "0" → removes leading zeros to get the canonical form
  - .zfill(3) → re-pads to 3 digits for use as the dictionary key (e.g., "1" → "001")


