9. RESPONSE GENERATOR (app/services/response_generator.py)
================================================================================

The response generator turns the structured (intent, entities, document) data into human-readable
text that gets sent back to the user.

INTENT ROUTING:
  generate_response() is a single function that uses if/elif branching on the intent label.
  Each intent has a dedicated handler:

  "document_status" + document found:
    Calls _format_document_status(document) to produce a rich, formatted response.

  "document_status" + no PDID:
    Returns a prompt asking the user for their PDID. The session context simultaneously
    records pending_intent="document_status" so the next message is handled correctly.

  "document_status" + PDID given but not found:
    Returns an error message with the PDID the user provided, so they can verify it.

  "follow_up" + document found:
    Same as document_status with data — calls _format_document_status().

  "follow_up" + PDID but not found / no PDID:
    Appropriate error messages asking for a PDID.

  "greeting": Randomly picks from 3 greeting response templates, so the bot doesn't sound
              repetitive when users say hello.

  "help": Returns a formatted help message listing the bot's capabilities.

  "complaint": Randomly picks from 2 empathetic complaint responses.

  "thanks": Randomly picks from 4 thank-you response variations.

  "goodbye": Randomly picks from 4 goodbye response variations.

  Fallback (unknown or unhandled): Returns a helpful message explaining what the bot can do.

RESPONSE VARIATION:
  For conversational intents (greeting, thanks, goodbye, complaint), random.choice() picks
  from a list of pre-written response templates. This makes the bot feel more natural and less
  robotic compared to always returning the exact same string.

DOCUMENT STATUS FORMATTING (_format_document_status):
  This function builds the detailed status reply. It:
  - Shows a PDID header with emoji (📄)
  - Lists accountable person, title, status (with ✅ or 🔄 emoji), current location,
    current action, origin office, creator, creation date, total processing time, office count
  - Adds a full Route History section listing every office the document passed through,
    showing who held it, what action was taken, TAT (turnaround time), and timestamps
  - The currently active stop is marked with a 📍 emoji and "Currently here" label
  - Past stops show "handled by" while the current stop shows "held by" for clarity


