10. DATABASE LAYER
================================================================================

────────────────────────────────────────────────
10a. ORM MODELS (app/db/models.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────

Three SQLAlchemy ORM models map to three MySQL tables:

  sessions TABLE:
    - id (VARCHAR 36, PRIMARY KEY): UUID string identifying the conversation session
    - created_at (DATETIME): When the session was first created
    - last_active (DATETIME): Updated on every request to track session activity
    - context (JSON): Stores the session's memory between turns:
        * pending_intent: "document_status" if we're waiting for a PDID
        * last_pdid: The last PDID mentioned in this session

  chat_logs TABLE:
    - id (INTEGER, AUTO INCREMENT, PRIMARY KEY)
    - session_id (VARCHAR 36, FOREIGN KEY → sessions.id, INDEXED): Links to the session
    - role (VARCHAR 10): "user" or "bot"
    - message (TEXT): The full message content
    - intent (VARCHAR 50, NULLABLE): Only set for user messages
    - confidence (FLOAT, NULLABLE): Classification confidence, only for user messages
    - entities (JSON, NULLABLE): Extracted entities (e.g., {"pdid": "001"}), only for user messages
    - timestamp (DATETIME): When the message was recorded
    The cascade="all, delete-orphan" relationship means deleting a session automatically
    deletes all its associated chat logs.

  training_data TABLE:
    - id (INTEGER, AUTO INCREMENT, PRIMARY KEY)
    - text (TEXT): The training example text
    - intent (VARCHAR 50, INDEXED): The label for this example
    - created_at (DATETIME): When this training example was added
    This table allows adding new training examples via SQL and retraining via POST /api/train.

────────────────────────────────────────────────
10b. DATABASE CONNECTION (app/db/database.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────

SQLAlchemy's create_engine() is used to create a connection pool to MySQL.
get_db() is a FastAPI dependency that yields a database session per request and ensures
the session is always closed after the request completes (even if an exception occurs).

────────────────────────────────────────────────
10c. CHAT LOGGER (app/services/chat_logger.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────

log_message() is a simple utility that creates a ChatLog ORM object, adds it to the db session,
commits it, and returns the created record. It is called twice per request: once for the user
message (with intent, confidence, entities) and once for the bot reply (without those fields).


================================================================================
11. API LAYER
================================================================================

────────────────────────────────────────────────
11a. PYDANTIC SCHEMAS (app/schemas/chat.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────

Pydantic models define the exact shape of every request and response body. FastAPI uses these
for automatic JSON serialization/deserialization, input validation, and Swagger documentation.

  ChatRequest:
    - message (str, required, 1–1000 chars): The user's message
    - session_id (str, optional): UUID from a previous response to continue a conversation
    - language (str, default "en"): Language preference — "en" for English, "tl" for Filipino

  ChatResponse:
    - reply (str): The AI's response text
    - session_id (str): Session UUID (pass this back in the next request)
    - intent (str): What the classifier determined the user wanted
    - confidence (float): How certain the classifier is (0.0 to 1.0)
    - entities (dict): Extracted data like {"pdid": "001"}

  TrainRequest:
    - source (str, default "csv"): "csv" or "database" — where to load training data from

  TrainResponse:
    - status, num_samples, num_intents, intents, training_accuracy

  HealthResponse:
    - status, model_loaded, model_intents

  TTSRequest:
    - text (str, required, 1–5000 chars): Text to convert to speech
    - voice (str, default "en-US-GuyNeural"): Which neural voice to use

────────────────────────────────────────────────
11b. REST ENDPOINTS (app/api/routes.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────

All routes are registered under the /api prefix via APIRouter. There are four endpoints:

  POST /api/chat (30 requests/minute per IP)
    The main chat endpoint. Receives a ChatRequest, calls process_message() from the
    conversation engine, and returns a ChatResponse. All ChatRequest validation is handled
    automatically by Pydantic before the function is even called.

  POST /api/train (5 requests/minute per IP)
    Triggers retraining of the intent classifier. If source="csv", it reads from the training
    CSV file. If source="database", it queries all rows from the training_data table and trains
    from those. Returns training statistics.

  GET /api/health (no rate limit)
    Returns whether the ML model is loaded and which intent classes it knows. Used by monitoring
    systems and for quick sanity checks.

  POST /api/tts (20 requests/minute per IP)
    Text-to-Speech endpoint. Accepts text and a voice name, returns an MP3 audio stream.
    (Detailed explanation in section 13.)


================================================================================
12. RATE LIMITER (app/rate_limiter.py)
================================================================================

A single Limiter instance is created using slowapi and keyed by get_remote_address (the client's
IP address). This instance is imported and used in two places:

  1. In main.py: attached to app.state and a custom RateLimitExceeded handler is registered
  2. In routes.py: each route uses @limiter.limit("N/minute") as a decorator

When a client exceeds its limit, the custom exception handler returns:
  HTTP 429 Too Many Requests
  {"detail": "Too many requests. Please slow down."}

Limits per endpoint:
  - /api/chat:  30 requests per minute
  - /api/tts:   20 requests per minute
  - /api/train:  5 requests per minute
  - /api/health: no limit (lightweight health check)


================================================================================
13. TEXT-TO-SPEECH (TTS) FEATURE
================================================================================

The TTS feature converts the AI's text reply into audio using Microsoft Edge Neural TTS voices
via the edge-tts Python library. This streams neural-quality speech audio.

HOW THE TTS ENDPOINT WORKS (POST /api/tts):

  STEP 1 — TEXT CLEANING (_strip_markdown):
    Before synthesizing speech, markdown formatting and emojis are stripped from the text
    because TTS engines would read them literally ("asterisk asterisk Document Status asterisk
    asterisk" instead of just "Document Status"). The cleaning performs:
    - Remove bold markers: **text** → text
    - Remove italic markers: *text* → text
    - Remove all emojis and symbols (Unicode ranges for emoji/symbol blocks)
    - Expand "No." abbreviation to "Number" for natural reading
    - Remove "• " bullet points
    - Convert newlines to ". " pauses for more natural speech flow
    - Collapse extra whitespace

  STEP 2 — LANGUAGE DETECTION & VOICE SELECTION:
    The requested voice is used by default. However, if the voice is NOT already the Filipino
    voice (fil-PH-AngeloNeural), langdetect.detect() is run on the cleaned text. If the text
    is detected as Tagalog ("tl"), the voice is automatically switched to fil-PH-AngeloNeural.
    This means even if the frontend sends the English voice, Filipino responses will automatically
    use the correct Filipino voice.

  STEP 3 — VOICE VALIDATION:
    Only voices in the ALLOWED_VOICES set are accepted:
    - "en-US-GuyNeural" (English male)
    - "fil-PH-AngeloNeural" (Filipino male)
    Any other voice string returns HTTP 400.

  STEP 4 — AUDIO GENERATION:
    edge_tts.Communicate(text, voice) is called. The audio is streamed in chunks. All audio
    chunks are collected into an in-memory BytesIO buffer.

  STEP 5 — STREAMING RESPONSE:
    The BytesIO buffer is returned as a StreamingResponse with media_type="audio/mpeg". The
    frontend receives a binary MP3 stream.

AVAILABLE NEURALTTS VOICES:
  - en-US-GuyNeural:     English, male, US accent
  - fil-PH-AngeloNeural: Filipino, male, Philippine accent


================================================================================
14. MULTI-LANGUAGE SUPPORT (TRANSLATION & TTS)
================================================================================

The system achieves bilingual (English/Filipino) support through three cooperating mechanisms:

MECHANISM 1 — FRONTEND LANGUAGE SELECTION:
  The web-app has a language select dropdown with "English" and "Filipino" options. When the
  user selects Filipino, the "language: tl" field is sent in API requests.

MECHANISM 2 — AUTO-DETECTION IN CONVERSATION ENGINE:
  Even without the frontend explicitly setting the language, if the user types in Tagalog/Filipino,
  langdetect will detect the language and trigger translation anyway. This means Filipino users
  who just type naturally get Filipino responses automatically.

MECHANISM 3 — TTS VOICE AUTO-SELECTION:
  The web-app maps the language dropdown to a voice (en-US-GuyNeural or fil-PH-AngeloNeural)
  when calling /api/tts. Additionally, the server-side TTS endpoint also auto-detects Filipino
  text and overrides the voice if needed — a double safety net.

TRANSLATION FLOW:
  English response → langdetect checks → if Filipino: GoogleTranslator('en' → 'tl') → Filipino response
  The translation uses deep-translator's GoogleTranslator which calls the Google Translate API.
  To avoid blocking the async event loop (GoogleTranslator is a synchronous library), it is
  wrapped in asyncio.to_thread() which runs it in a thread pool executor.

FAILURE SAFETY:
  Both translation and language detection are wrapped in try/except blocks. Any failure
  (network outage, API quota, unknown language) silently falls back to the English response
  rather than crashing the request.


