18. HOW MOCK MODE WORKS
================================================================================

When DTS_MOCK_MODE=True (the default for development):

  - No HTTP calls are made to the DTS API
  - MOCK_DOCUMENTS is loaded at startup from documents.json (if present) plus built-in samples
  - get_document(pdid) simply does a dictionary lookup against MOCK_DOCUMENTS
  - Built-in PDIDs 001, 002, 003 are always available:
      001: Leave Application — Juan Dela Cruz, In Progress at City Mayor's Office
      002: Purchase Request — office supplies, Completed at City Budget Office
      003: Travel Order — Pedro Reyes, In Progress at City Administrator's Office
  - documents.json can contain a real DTS API response; it will be parsed and added to the mock

This allows full development and testing without needing the real DTS infrastructure running.


================================================================================
19. HOW LIVE MODE WORKS
================================================================================

When DTS_MOCK_MODE=False:

  1. Set in .env: DTS_MOCK_MODE=false and DTS_API_BASE_URL=http://your-dts-server:port
  2. get_document(pdid) builds the URL: {DTS_API_BASE_URL}/api/documents/{pdid_clean}
  3. httpx.AsyncClient makes an async GET request with a 10-second timeout
  4. The raw JSON response is passed through parse_dts_document() to flatten it
  5. The parsed result is cached in _document_cache for 60 seconds
  6. 404 responses (document not found) are also cached to prevent redundant not-found calls
  7. HTTP errors return None (handled as "document not found" by the response generator)


================================================================================
20. MODEL TRAINING — HOW IT WORKS
================================================================================

The intent classifier can be trained in three ways:

WAY 1 — AUTOMATIC STARTUP TRAINING:
  If no model file exists at ml_models/intent_model.joblib but ml_data/intent_training.csv
  exists, the classifier is trained automatically when the server starts. This zero-config
  behavior means you can deploy to a new server and the model will train itself on first boot.

WAY 2 — MANUAL CLI TRAINING:
  Run: python scripts/train.py
  This reads the CSV, trains the model, and saves it. Useful during development to retrain
  without starting the full server.

WAY 3 — API-TRIGGERED RETRAINING:
  POST /api/train {"source": "csv"} or {"source": "database"}
  This allows retraining at runtime without restarting the server. After training, the new
  model is immediately active for all subsequent requests. Useful for adding new intents to
  production without downtime.

TRAINING DATA FORMAT (ml_data/intent_training.csv):
  A CSV with two columns: "text" and "intent"
  Example rows:
    "What is the status of my document?",document_status
    "Check PDID 100",document_status
    "Hello",greeting
    "Thank you",thanks

To add a new intent:
  1. Add training examples to the CSV (at least 10-20 per intent for good accuracy)
  2. Call POST /api/train {"source": "csv"}
  3. The new intent is immediately available


