21. MULTI-TURN CONVERSATION — HOW CONTEXT IS MAINTAINED
================================================================================

Every client receives a session_id on their first request. The client must pass this session_id
back in subsequent requests to maintain context within the same conversation.

EXAMPLE MULTI-TURN SESSION:

  Turn 1: User says "What is the status of my document?"
    → Intent: document_status
    → No PDID in message
    → Response: "What is the Tracking No. of your document?"
    → Session context saved: {pending_intent: "document_status"}
    → session_id "abc-123" returned to client

  Turn 2: User says "001" (with session_id: "abc-123")
    → Session loaded from DB, context: {pending_intent: "document_status"}
    → Intent detected: "unknown" (just a number doesn't clearly map to an intent)
    → Entity extracted: pdid = "001"
    → pending_intent "document_status" IS set → intent overridden to "follow_up"
    → pending_intent cleared in context
    → Document 001 looked up → full status returned
    → Session context saved: {pending_intent: null, last_pdid: "001"}

  Turn 3: User says "Who is currently holding it?" (with session_id: "abc-123")
    → Session loaded, context: {last_pdid: "001"}
    → Intent: document_status
    → No PDID in message, BUT last_pdid = "001" exists in context
    → entities["pdid"] = "001" injected from context
    → Document 001 looked up again → reply includes current holder info

This creates a natural, flowing conversation without the user having to repeat the PDID
in every message.


